ich should be fine since the hint is explicit anyway. The real problem is that both the broadcast and AQE jobs ran in parallel, competing for CPU resources and making them both slower than the baseline which ran alone. To properly validate that broadcast is faster, I should re-run it in isolation after fixing the AQE job.\n\nSo the minimum fixes needed are: first, the AQE job has `skewedPartitionThresholdInBytes=1b` which treats every partition as skewed, creating massive splitting overhead instead of providing any speedup—I need to change that to `256mb`. Second, the concurrency issue means both optimization jobs ran simultaneously, which skewed the performance results.\n\nMy plan is to delete both jobs, fix the AQE YAML by updating the base64-encoded Python script to use the correct threshold value, then run broadcast first and wait for it to complete, followed by AQE, so I can get accurate sequential results to compare.\n\nI'm also checking the spark-cluster.yaml for potential issues—the `unset SPARK_MASTER_PORT` before starting the master looks defensive rather than buggy, since it ensures the default 7077 port is used if the image has set it incorrectly.\n\nThe real issue I'm identifying is the AQE script's threshold value of `\"1b\"` for `skewedPartitionThresholdInBytes`, which is causing AQE to over-trigger and create performance problems.\n\nI also suspect the jobs ran simultaneously, creating resource contention that masked the broadcast optimization's benefits. I need to fix the AQE configuration and run the jobs sequentially to see the real performance difference.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11331,"cache_read_input_tokens":45267,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11331},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id